"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-paris-2024-olympics-what-time-does-benjamin-richardson-run-for-team-sa\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbParis 2024 Olympics: What time does Benjamin Richardson run for Team SA?  The 100m semi-finals are not far away now.  Team SA has three representatives in the 100m semi-finals, a blue-chip event at the Paris 2024 Olympics. 20-year-old Benjamin Richardson is one of them.  It's the shortest event on the track but it's arguably the most glamorous. South Africa will have three representatives across three semi-finals tonight at the Olympic Games. Team SA, impressively, has three representatives across the three semi-finals. Veteran sprinter Akani Simbine, now 30 years old, hopes to improve on his fourth place in the final in Tokyo and fifth in the final in Rio back in 2016. Richardson, only 20, runs his semi-final onSunday 04 August at 20:23. He will run against Kenya's Ferdinand Omanyala and 30-year-old Canadian Andre De Grasse, a man with six Olympic medals to his name throughout an impressive career.  The final runs at 21:50.  One of the most electrifying performers across any sporting code, Jamaican GOAT Usain Bolt changed the game of sprinting and it'll never be the same. Standing 1.95m tall, many pundits thought Bolt was too tall to be a sprinter but he made a mockery of those claims, becoming the greatest quick man the world has ever seen and entertaining millions along the way. LikeTatjana Smith, he was never the fastest starter but it's all about how you finish. Bolt crossed the line first in eight Olympic sprint finals, including an unprecedented triple-double in the 100m and 200m events across three consecutive games in Beijing, London and Rio. Will we ever see someone like him again? Three Jamaicans are in the running for the title of world's fastest man and Olympic champion in 2024; Oblique Seville, Ackeem Blake and Kishane Thompson.  Let us know by clicking on the comment tab below this article or emailinginfo@thesouthafrican.com. Meanwhile, you can also send a WhatsApp to 060 011 021 1. Follow@TheSAnews on XandThe South African on Facebookfor your social fix.  Catch the latest from the French capital on our dedicated Olympicspage.  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no visitors will be accepted without an appointment.  South Africa- Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd - Registration Number: 2005/028472/07 - Address: Regus Business Centre, 1st Floor, Block B, North Park, Black River Park, 2 Fir Street, Observatory, Cape Town, 7925, South Africa  Copyright Blue Sky Publications (